explanation:
 Yes, it is possible to match all words in a phrase using a regular expression. The regular expression you provided, `[A-Za-z]*`, matches any sequence of letters, but it is only matching the first word because the `*` character means "match the preceding character zero or more times," and it is matching zero occurrences of letters after the first word.

To match all the words in a phrase, you can use the regular expression `\w+`. The `\w` character class matches any word character (equivalent to `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`), and the `+` character means "match the preceding character one or more times." This regular expression will match any sequence of one or more word characters.

Here is an example of how you can use this regular expression in C#:

```
using System;
using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string input = "hello how are you";
        string pattern = @"\w+";

        MatchCollection matches = Regex.Matches(input, pattern);

        foreach (Match match in matches)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(match.Value);
        }
    }
}
```

This will output:

```
hello
how
are
you
```

